{"$ambrosia":"aero:interactive:9417ac60-5f60-11ea-8e69-affb2224d7e8:*","$id":"ec6262e0-44df-11ed-8b94-b61b88796792","$workspaceId":"7fff47c0-44d6-11ed-bcef-d5307f42495c","$projectId":"86cb0040-44df-11ed-8442-dbcbc27803ca","annotations":[],"configSchemaVersion":"/pluginGenericSchema/v1","config":{"stage":{"sections":[{"rows":[{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"heading-two","ref":"a5d88daf-eedb-4e11-b2a9-cc492175253c","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Rule 1: Comparing and Combining Values","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"79e75338-7586-4171-92a5-46719913feff"},{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"815f6fe4-fcea-43f5-b82f-291936411f6b","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Our first rule is that it is only possible to compare or combine values at the same point in time.","marks":[{"type":"italic"}]},{"object":"text","text":" This rule restates a conclusion from the last section: Only cash flows in the same units can be compared or combined. A dollar today and a dollar in one year are not equivalent. Having money now is more valuable than having money in the future; if you have the money today you can invest it and earn interest.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"075e934f-59f3-4ad2-800b-dba0da680008"},{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"a730dcfa-3137-4612-a4bd-d143eb653d56","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"To compare or combine cash flows that occur at different points in time, you first need to convert the cash flows into the same units by moving them to the same point in time. The next two rules show how to move the cash flows on the timeline.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"6392b5c3-16ef-4a5b-85ce-4b244a7f2c6b"}]}]}]},{"cssClass":"aside-group Sidebar_1Aside","rows":[{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"heading-two","ref":"63ac827b-0de1-4737-a540-87bc1cab11fe","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Common Mistake: Summing Cash Flows Across Time","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"2c41feff-a73f-43b7-9624-647d0cae9dd7"},{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"8265f7ce-44f8-447a-b0a6-138e542aeec1","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Once you understand the time value of money, our first rule may seem straightforward. However, it is very common, especially for those who have not studied finance, to violate this rule, simply treating all cash flows as comparable regardless of when they are received. One example is in sports contracts. In 2019, Mike Trout signed a contract extension with the Los Angeles Angels that was repeatedly referred to as a “$430 million” contract. The $430 million comes from simply adding up all the payments Trout would receive over the 12 years of the contract—treating dollars received in 12 years the same as dollars received today. The same thing occurred when Lionel Messi signed a contract extension with FC Barcelona in 2017, giving him a “$320 million” contract through 2021, and in 2011 when Albert Pujols agreed to a “240 million” ten-year contract with the Los Angeles Angels.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"d6c397ac-cede-4ba9-8e8d-1eae9f78be26"},{"type":"stage-element-image","config":{"url":{"$ambrosia":"aero:asset:upload","urn":"urn:aero:7596bed0-44e0-11ed-9967-59bbd5f34c83","asset":{"urn":"urn:aero:7596bed0-44e0-11ed-9967-59bbd5f34c83","asset":{"assetProvider":"ALFRESCO","id":"7596bed0-44e0-11ed-9967-59bbd5